About Dataset¶

CONTEXT¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

OBJECTIVE¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

# Create a function that groups all methods of interest and apply to each column of the dataframe
def column_describer(df, col):
    # Create an empty DataFrame
    result_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=["Value", "Count", "Percentage"])

    # Calculate value counts and percentages
    value_counts = df[col].value_counts(normalize=True).head(10)
    for i, v in value_counts.items():
        count = df[col].value_counts()[i]
        percentage = v * 100
        result_df = result_df.append({"Value": i, "Count": count, "Percentage": f"{percentage :.2f}%"}, ignore_index=True)

    # Add a row for unique values
    unique_values = df[col].nunique()
    result_df = result_df.append({"Value": "Unique Values", "Count": unique_values, "Percentage": ""}, ignore_index=True)

    return result_df

In [14]:
# Function to categorize order frequency of the customers
def customer_frequency(value):
    if value == 1:
        return "One order customer"
    elif value <=4:
        return "2 to 4 orders"
    else:
        return "Over 4 orders"
In [15]:
# Apply the function to the frequency variable and get the count of each category, to plot it after
frequency = df["customer_id"].value_counts().apply(customer_frequency)
customer_freq = frequency.value_counts()
In [16]:

# Function to group costs in range of values
def cost_category(value):
    if (value) <= 5 :
        return "0-5$"
    elif (value) <= 10 :
        return "6-10$"
    elif (value) <= 15 :
        return "11-15$"
    elif (value) <= 20 :
        return "16-20$"
    elif (value) <= 25 :
        return "21-25$"
    elif (value) <= 30 :
        return "26-30$"
    else:
        return "Over 30$"

In [74]:
# Create a function that groups total time 
def time_category(value):
    if (value) <= 40 :
        return "< 40 minutes"
    elif (value) <= 50 :
        return "41- 50 minutes"
    elif (value) <= 60 :
        return "51 - 60 minutes"
    else:
        return "Over 60 minutes"
In [75]:
# Order the values of the categories 
time_order = pd.CategoricalDtype(
    ["< 40 minutes", "41- 50 minutes", "51 - 60 minutes", "Over 60 minutes"],
    ordered=True)
In [76]:
# Apply the function created
category_time = top_30_restaurants_time["total_time"].apply(time_category).astype(time_order)

ax.set_title("Correlation Matrix Grouped Time vs Top 30 Restaurants")
plt.show()

However, there are instances where the total time exceeds 60 minutes, as well as a smaller number of cases where the total time is less than 40 minutes.

Conclusions and Recommendations¶

Conclusions¶

  • Top Restaurants: Shake Shack, The Meatball Shop and Blue Ribbon chain restaurant. They stand with the most orders (219, 132, 292), and therefore more revenues (3579.53 , 2145.21, 4784.07) . For the most rated restaurants, they also outstand with ratings over 4. The top 20 customers prefer the mentioned restaurants over the rest. The prices of the orders are around the 11 to 20 dollars interval. They maintain optimal food preparation and delivery times.

  • Prefered Cuisine: The prefered cuisine type is the American style, but the top 20 customers prefer the Japanese style slightly more. They both maintain prices around the 16 dollars. The Italian and Chinese cuisine is one to keep an eye on as well.

  • Cost of the order: The cost of the order is on average 16.50 dollars across all restaurants. However, Korean and Vietnamese average cost are the lowest of all, with a median value of 12 dollars. French cuisine type is the most expensive, with a median of 20 dollars.

  • There is lack of significant correlation between cost of the order and food preparation and delivery time. Internal factors within the restaurant, such as increased demand or other operational considerations may be the root cause of the increased food preparation and delivery times.

  • Prefered Day of the Week: Weekend is the prefered moment to make orders for the customers. Customers have placed 1351 orders on weekend compared to 547 orders on weekdays. Probably customers choose to relax or minimize the activity during weekends.

  • Ratings: Spanish cuisine receives the highest ratings, albeit representing a small portion of the dataset.

  • There seems to be no correlation between rating and food preparation time and cost of the order. Other factors seem to influence ratings beyond these basic metrics.

  • Preparation and Delivery times: Korean cuisine consistently exhibits shorter preparation and delivery times. (25 and 20 minutes respectively).

  • Delivery times generally tend to be shorter on weekends (22 minutes on weekends, compared to 28 minutes on weekdays), possibly due to lighter traffic during those days.

  • Food preparation times are similar across the week (around 28 minutes).

Recommendations¶

  • Consider strategies to minimize “Not given” ratings. By reducing instances of “Not Given” ratings, the food aggregator company can effectively identify the highest-rated restaurants. This could enable the implementation of targeted strategies to enhance overall performance.
  • Consider focused marketing efforts for renowned establishments such as Blue Ribbon, RedFarm, Shake Shack, and The Meatball Shop. These restaurants consistently demonstrate high revenues, high order volumes, and overall good ratings.
  • Leverage the overall preparation, delivery time and average low costs associated with Korean cuisine as a unique selling point. Highlighting efficient service can contribute to making Korean dishes more popular among customers.
  • Develop marketing strategies specifically aimed at increasing weekend orders. Emphasize shorter delivery times during weekends, leveraging the lighter traffic conditions to attract more customers.
  • Given their exceptional ratings, explore targeted promotional efforts to elevate the popularity of Spanish cuisine. Highlight the distinctive flavors and quality associated with Spanish dishes.
